OK.

00:03:09.180 --> 00:03:14.220
We don't have a very
specific course text,

00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:16.830
but like I said, in some case,
we'll give you review articles.

00:03:16.830 --> 00:03:18.660
We'll give you handouts.

00:03:18.660 --> 00:03:20.790
There's a few good books
though that you may want

00:03:20.790 --> 00:03:23.160
to browse through on occasion.

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:26.100
So depending on what's
your main interest,

00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:28.590
the book by Allen and
Tildesley is an old classic

00:03:28.590 --> 00:03:30.810
on computer
simulation of liquids.

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:33.690
In the end, it's really a
book on molecular dynamics.

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:37.530
It's quite old by now,
but it's a very good basis

00:03:37.530 --> 00:03:39.000
to start from.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.930
It doesn't have the
most advanced algorithms

00:03:42.930 --> 00:03:45.120
or new techniques in it
per se, but it's really

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:49.020
still a very good book.

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:53.700
Rob Phillips wrote a newer
book on, essentially,

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:56.100
modeling which both
contains continuum

00:03:56.100 --> 00:03:57.750
and atomistic modeling.

00:03:57.750 --> 00:04:01.110
That has a heavy slant
on mechanical behavior.

00:04:01.110 --> 00:04:02.910
So if you're more
interested in that,

00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:06.720
that may be a book that
you want to look into.

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:12.360
Jensen is one of my favorites,
although it's heavily

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:16.709
chemistry focused, modeling
of molecules and so,

00:04:16.709 --> 00:04:20.160
but it's actually
very clearly written.

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:23.790
And Thijssen is a
great book if you

00:04:23.790 --> 00:04:25.890
want to focus on ab
initio methods and quantum

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:29.130
mechanics, which we'll
do later in the course.

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:32.260
And Frenkel and
Smit is my favorite

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:34.110
for statistical
mechanics, if you

00:04:34.110 --> 00:04:36.660
want to learn about the
statistical mechanics

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:38.520
of molecular dynamics
and Monte Carlo

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:41.580
methods and things like that.

00:04:41.580 --> 00:04:46.810
This is really a very, very
good book, very thoroughly done.

00:04:46.810 --> 00:04:47.310
OK.

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:54.600
So I should say a few words
about the course objectives.

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:58.080
When we designed this
course, we deliberately

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:03.420
made it a somewhat introductory
and overview subject.

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:07.480
We wanted this to be a course
that was not for experts.

00:05:07.480 --> 00:05:10.410
So if you already know
everything about ab initio

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:13.020
methods and molecular
dynamics and Monte Carlo,

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:15.270
you may actually start
getting bored after a while.

00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:18.960
We really wanted this to be a
course that an average graduate

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:21.630
student, somebody who was
doing experimental research

00:05:21.630 --> 00:05:24.420
for example, also could take.

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:26.310
So what we mainly
try to do is teach

00:05:26.310 --> 00:05:30.660
the tools of modern
computation materials science

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:34.600
and how they can be applied
to diverse materials problems.

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:38.940
So we will give you technical
details of the tools

00:05:38.940 --> 00:05:42.510
but only to the extent that
you need them to understand

00:05:42.510 --> 00:05:44.340
how you can apply them.

00:05:44.340 --> 00:05:44.967
OK?

00:05:44.967 --> 00:05:46.800
So we will, of course,
tell you, for example

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:49.770
what molecular dynamics is,
what the basis is of it,

00:05:49.770 --> 00:05:51.600
what some of the
basic algorithms are.

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:55.590
But we will not go into the
very detailed, novel algorithms

00:05:55.590 --> 00:05:59.070
to make it a factor of too
fast or something like that.

00:05:59.070 --> 00:06:02.010
So we will not do a lot of
detailed algorithmic work

00:06:02.010 --> 00:06:03.160
in the course.

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:05.820
So there is a heavy focusing on
understanding the physics that

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:09.420
goes in and because of that the
physics and the applications

00:06:09.420 --> 00:06:12.600
that can come out.

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:18.150
So because of that,
you will occasionally

00:06:18.150 --> 00:06:22.200
see us teach materials theory
rather than computation.

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:25.470
Because in some cases, I feel
the hard part of computation

00:06:25.470 --> 00:06:27.810
is knowing what to
compute, and for that,

00:06:27.810 --> 00:06:29.670
you need some basic
materials here.

00:06:29.670 --> 00:06:33.180
Like when I do a case study
on diffusion, towards the end,

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:36.630
I may have to tell you a little
bit about diffusion theory,

00:06:36.630 --> 00:06:40.350
activation barriers and
correlation factors,

00:06:40.350 --> 00:06:42.870
because then we can actually
connect that to the things

00:06:42.870 --> 00:06:47.340
we can calculate.

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:51.330
So you should think of this
as a course in modeling

00:06:51.330 --> 00:06:55.080
towards material science
and materials application.

00:06:55.080 --> 00:06:58.230
We do very little purely
numerical work, actually almost

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:01.290
none to speak of.

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:03.150
OK.

00:07:03.150 --> 00:07:06.120
So the way I see atomistic
modeling is really

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:10.500
as the integration of
these four basic fields--

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:13.740
physics, mathematics, computer
science, and material science,

00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:18.540
and that's how we'll
tend to approach it.

