00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:05.780
So I wanted to talk a
little about the growing

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:06.830
importance of modeling.

00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:13.760
I started computational
modeling in 1988,

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:17.960
when it was a rarity, especially
in material science department.

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:19.680
Now, you see it everywhere.

00:11:19.680 --> 00:11:22.460
It's one of these
enormously growing fields.

00:11:22.460 --> 00:11:25.610
You'd be surprised, but even
atomistic level modeling is

00:11:25.610 --> 00:11:27.980
probably now more
intensively done in industry

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:30.800
than it is in academia.

00:11:30.800 --> 00:11:32.990
We think of it as a
broader academic subject,

00:11:32.990 --> 00:11:37.460
but it really has taken a
foothold in corporations.

00:11:37.460 --> 00:11:39.680
I wanted to show you
a few examples of how

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:43.460
I think that really showed
the impact of modeling,

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:46.070
where modeling is used to
make important decisions.

00:11:46.070 --> 00:11:50.000
This is a picture
from the ASCI Program.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.590
When the US was planning to sign
the Nuclear Stockpile Treaty,

00:11:54.590 --> 00:11:56.060
which meant that--

00:11:56.060 --> 00:12:00.260
the nuclear stockpile treaty is
basically that you cannot test

00:12:00.260 --> 00:12:03.050
nuclear missiles anymore
by setting them off.

00:12:03.050 --> 00:12:06.020
Because essentially that's
so the US was concerned

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:08.490
how could we verify
the reliability

00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:10.490
of nuclear missiles,
because they're essentially

00:12:10.490 --> 00:12:14.090
going to sit for 100
years in their silo.

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:15.950
And there was an enormous
program in the US

00:12:15.950 --> 00:12:18.830
for, literally, they would just
blow one up once in a while

00:12:18.830 --> 00:12:22.220
to see if it still
works, and now, they

00:12:22.220 --> 00:12:24.380
can't do that anymore.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:26.240
Although, the US has
actually not ratified

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:28.370
the Nuclear Stockpile
Treaty, they still

00:12:28.370 --> 00:12:30.860
are sticking with it.

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:33.830
And some, I don't
know, smart people

00:12:33.830 --> 00:12:36.230
decided what are we going to
do with all this money which

00:12:36.230 --> 00:12:37.730
was several hundred
million dollars.

00:12:37.730 --> 00:12:39.290
So they decided,
well, we're going

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:43.190
to model the reliability
of nuclear missiles,

00:12:43.190 --> 00:12:45.620
and that led to what's called
ASCI Program, the Advanced

00:12:45.620 --> 00:12:48.470
Simulation Computing
Initiative, which is literally

00:12:48.470 --> 00:12:52.220
one of the largest computational
modeling programs in the world

00:12:52.220 --> 00:12:53.030
now.

00:12:53.030 --> 00:12:55.790
It's definitely
not all atomistics,

00:12:55.790 --> 00:12:59.150
but there definitely is a large
atomistic component on it.

00:12:59.150 --> 00:13:02.060
And the whole idea was,
as they call it cynically,

00:13:02.060 --> 00:13:04.940
it's modeling from
button to boom.

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:07.490
So they model everything--
aging of plutonium,

00:13:07.490 --> 00:13:12.110
aging of corrosion of
the alloys, corrosion

00:13:12.110 --> 00:13:13.850
of the electronics.

00:13:13.850 --> 00:13:17.840
Whether actually the time
is actually ripe for that

00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:18.710
is another question.

00:13:18.710 --> 00:13:20.870
Whether you can reliably
model all these things

00:13:20.870 --> 00:13:21.740
