PROFESSOR: London, close by.

00:18:26.322 --> 00:18:27.560
OK.

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:31.610
Where knowing what
the composition is

00:18:31.610 --> 00:18:35.900
of the mantle in the Earth, both
the composition and the phases

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:38.870
that are present, is an
enormously difficult problem.

00:18:38.870 --> 00:18:41.180
But it's one of these
actually quite literally

00:18:41.180 --> 00:18:45.350
hot problems in
materials geology.

00:18:45.350 --> 00:18:48.110
We know that there's iron
and magnesium and oxygen

00:18:48.110 --> 00:18:51.390
and silicon and a few other
things, but in the end,

00:18:51.390 --> 00:18:53.270
we really don't know
what phases they

00:18:53.270 --> 00:18:55.550
form, what their
elastic properties are,

00:18:55.550 --> 00:18:56.540
and things like that.

00:18:56.540 --> 00:18:58.730
And the experiments
are really hard.

00:18:58.730 --> 00:19:01.910
Somewhere in the
mantle, pressures

00:19:01.910 --> 00:19:08.960
are I think anywhere from
50 to maybe 300 gigapascals.

00:19:08.960 --> 00:19:11.208
These are really hard
experiments to do.

00:19:11.208 --> 00:19:13.250
And I was yesterday at
the University of Illinois

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:15.940
in the Department of
Geology, and they showed me

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:18.440
the way they do high pressure
experiments with diamond anvil

00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:18.940
cells.

00:19:18.940 --> 00:19:21.650
You need about a 1/4 to 1/2 a
carat diamond, first of all,

00:19:21.650 --> 00:19:24.740
so these people have a safe in
their lab, it's pretty cool,

00:19:24.740 --> 00:19:27.140
where they're diamonds sit.

00:19:27.140 --> 00:19:30.920
And then you have to make
really small samples,

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:33.390
pushed very hard on them
with a diamond anvil.

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:34.130
OK?

00:19:34.130 --> 00:19:35.600
So you're really pushing on it.

00:19:35.600 --> 00:19:37.093
This sits in an
enormous container,

00:19:37.093 --> 00:19:38.510
because you have
to keep a hundred

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:40.490
gigapascal on this
thing, and then you

00:19:40.490 --> 00:19:42.260
have to characterize it.

00:19:42.260 --> 00:19:43.310
Can you imagine?

00:19:43.310 --> 00:19:45.500
So you have this
enormous holder,

00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:47.990
because you're putting
it under 100 GPa,

00:19:47.990 --> 00:19:50.542
and you've got to see inside.

00:19:50.542 --> 00:19:52.250
So they're really hard
experiments to do.

00:19:52.250 --> 00:19:54.630
You can't really control
the temperature very well.

00:19:54.630 --> 00:19:56.300
So this is where
modeling is great,

00:19:56.300 --> 00:19:57.920
if you believe the answers.

00:19:57.920 --> 00:20:01.160
So a lot of people do
computational quantum mechanics

00:20:01.160 --> 00:20:04.220
on phases under high pressure.

00:20:04.220 --> 00:20:06.860
High pressure is
trivial in computation.

00:20:06.860 --> 00:20:09.380
Just push on it, you change
the lattice parameter,

00:20:09.380 --> 00:20:10.340
and you constrain it.

00:20:10.340 --> 00:20:13.430
You control the variable,
and you have high pressure.

00:20:13.430 --> 00:20:16.090
300 gigapascal, no problem.

00:20:16.090 --> 00:20:16.590
OK.

00:20:20.660 --> 00:20:23.450
This one I particularly like.

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:26.613
There was an article
in the New York Times.

00:20:26.613 --> 00:20:29.030
This is when science made the
New York Times which doesn't

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:31.460
happen too often, in 1999.

00:20:31.460 --> 00:20:35.720
The people had basically
been able to visualize

00:20:35.720 --> 00:20:41.210
electron densities, orbitals,
and that's the left picture.

00:20:41.210 --> 00:20:42.950
This is I think in copper oxide.

00:20:42.950 --> 00:20:45.230
I forgot what this is.

00:20:45.230 --> 00:20:47.540
In some copper oxide,
where they literally

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:49.190
were able to visualize
the orbitals,

00:20:49.190 --> 00:20:53.270
and they look like d
orbitals, don't they?

00:20:53.270 --> 00:20:56.390
This is actually one
of these things that

00:20:56.390 --> 00:20:59.030
is quite an experimental feat.

00:20:59.030 --> 00:21:01.010
It made the New York
Times, because people

00:21:01.010 --> 00:21:03.410
could do it experimentally.

00:21:03.410 --> 00:21:06.167
This is trivial computationally.

00:21:06.167 --> 00:21:08.000
When you do computational
quantum mechanics,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:11.300
you will get orbitals
and orbital populations.

00:21:11.300 --> 00:21:14.390
That doesn't mean that
the experiment is useless.

00:21:14.390 --> 00:21:15.230
OK?

00:21:15.230 --> 00:21:18.080
Because the experiment could
be the critical verification

00:21:18.080 --> 00:21:20.720
of what you do in your theory,
but I'm just showing you

00:21:20.720 --> 00:21:23.030
that these things have an
enormously different level

00:21:23.030 --> 00:21:24.740
of complexity.

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:28.010
And if you're ever going
to use both computations

00:21:28.010 --> 00:21:31.730
and experiment, the one key
thing that will put you ahead

00:21:31.730 --> 00:21:35.450
is understanding what is
most efficient for a given

00:21:35.450 --> 00:21:38.570
problem, either
computation or experiment.

00:21:38.570 --> 00:21:45.150
Because the complexity of either
has no relation to each other.

00:21:45.150 --> 00:21:47.810
So for some
problems, computation

00:21:47.810 --> 00:21:51.050
is extremely efficient, and
experiment is really hard,

00:21:51.050 --> 00:21:53.150
and for some problems,
it's the other way around.

00:21:53.150 --> 00:21:55.340
And understanding
where to use what,

00:21:55.340 --> 00:21:56.930
if you're going to
use both, I think

00:21:56.930 --> 00:21:59.900
is the thing that would
really get you ahead.

00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:01.400
And unfortunately,
most of the time,

00:22:01.400 --> 00:22:03.400
that doesn't happen,
because usually people only

00:22:03.400 --> 00:22:06.362
do one of the two.

00:22:06.362 --> 00:22:07.820
Here, for example,
this is actually

00:22:07.820 --> 00:22:11.060
from Professor Marzari,
the electron density

00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:15.920
in lead titanate which is a
perovskite, a ferroelectric.

00:22:15.920 --> 00:22:19.250
So you see beautiful orbitals
without the graininess

00:22:19.250 --> 00:22:22.990
of experiments.

00:22:22.990 --> 00:22:27.070
The other thing
is, sometimes, you

00:22:27.070 --> 00:22:29.920
can do things fast
computationally.

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:32.870
This is out of my own work.

00:22:32.870 --> 00:22:37.030
One of the areas we work in is
predicting crystal structure.

00:22:37.030 --> 00:22:40.480
Typically, getting a phase
diagram of a material

00:22:40.480 --> 00:22:43.890
used to take about a PhD thesis.

00:22:43.890 --> 00:22:46.660
It takes you that long
to make all the samples,

00:22:46.660 --> 00:22:51.100
do the structural analysis,
get the phase boundaries.

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:57.490
In about a six month time frame,
we ran 15,000-- it says 10,000.

00:22:57.490 --> 00:22:59.140
We were up at 15,000--

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:01.960
first principles calculations
to find the structures,

00:23:01.960 --> 00:23:05.530
the ground-state structures
in 80 metallic systems, 80

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:07.400
binary metallic systems.

00:23:07.400 --> 00:23:13.640
So in some sense, we did 80 PhD
thesises in about six months.

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:16.030
So there are certain
things that you can now

00:23:16.030 --> 00:23:18.550
solve more efficiently
computationally

00:23:18.550 --> 00:23:19.710
than experimentally.

00:23:19.710 --> 00:23:21.460
And I think it makes
sense, like let's say

00:23:21.460 --> 00:23:23.800
you are looking for
structure of material,

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:26.590
to first do the
computation, and then

00:23:26.590 --> 00:23:30.070
when you need to resolve
issues, then do the experiment,

00:23:30.070 --> 00:23:35.050
rather than first blindly
do the experiment.

00:23:35.050 --> 00:23:39.020
And we'll talk a little more
later about these things.

00:23:39.020 --> 00:23:41.170
Control, we already
talked about control.

00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:42.430
That's the number one.

00:23:42.430 --> 00:23:47.320
Here's one of the first examples
of where I saw that applied.

00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:50.680
In the early '80s,
aluminum lithium

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:53.020
was one of the key
alloys that people

00:23:53.020 --> 00:23:54.790
thought of for airframes.

00:23:54.790 --> 00:24:00.202
Because of course now,
airframes are aluminum copper.

00:24:00.202 --> 00:24:01.660
If you want to make
it lighter, you

00:24:01.660 --> 00:24:02.952
have to go to lighter elements.

00:24:02.952 --> 00:24:05.560
Well, lithium is the
lightest solid element.

00:24:05.560 --> 00:24:08.740
So substituting the copper
away and using aluminum lithium

00:24:08.740 --> 00:24:11.480
alloys was supposed to
make really light alloys.

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:13.900
It didn't pan out, because
they're not very weldable.

00:24:13.900 --> 00:24:17.290
So you actually find very little
aluminum lithium on airplanes

00:24:17.290 --> 00:24:18.910
these days.

00:24:18.910 --> 00:24:23.860
But the key issue in
aluminum lithium is that--

00:24:23.860 --> 00:24:25.580
this is the stable
phase diagram.

00:24:25.580 --> 00:24:29.020
So there's an FCC solid solution
in equilibrium with a compound,

00:24:29.020 --> 00:24:31.090
but what actually
strengthens the material is

00:24:31.090 --> 00:24:34.030
a metastable precipitate
which is in here.

00:24:34.030 --> 00:24:38.260
And because it's metastable,
it's very hard to study,

00:24:38.260 --> 00:24:40.720
because to study it,
you need to make it big.

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:43.600
To strengthen the alloys,
you have to keep it small.

00:24:43.600 --> 00:24:45.640
But to study it,
like with microscopy,

00:24:45.640 --> 00:24:47.080
you need to make it big enough.

00:24:47.080 --> 00:24:48.970
But the problem is you can't
anneal the precipitate,

00:24:48.970 --> 00:24:49.970
because it's metastable.

00:24:49.970 --> 00:24:51.950
If you anneal it to
long, it goes away.

00:24:51.950 --> 00:24:52.450
OK.

00:24:52.450 --> 00:24:55.870
So this was a great
one for computation.

00:24:55.870 --> 00:24:57.910
In computation, something
that's metastable,

00:24:57.910 --> 00:25:01.000
you can easily make it stable
by not letting the system evolve

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:03.920
to whatever is stable, and
that's what was done here.

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:06.010
This is a calculated
phase diagram

00:25:06.010 --> 00:25:10.150
completely from first principles
with the stable equilibria

00:25:10.150 --> 00:25:13.540
in solid lines and then
the metastable equilibrium,

00:25:13.540 --> 00:25:16.150
this was the precipitant phase.

00:25:19.760 --> 00:25:21.620
And so you can just
isolate this thing

00:25:21.620 --> 00:25:24.170
and look at it separately.

00:25:24.170 --> 00:25:26.240
OK.

00:25:26.240 --> 00:25:29.450
Let me skip that one.

00:25:29.450 --> 00:25:32.060
You can use computation
often to prove or disprove

00:25:32.060 --> 00:25:37.070
hypotheses in cases where it's
hard to see experimentally.

00:25:37.070 --> 00:25:42.200
A really ongoing and long story
has been the defect in silicon.

00:25:42.200 --> 00:25:46.820
How do vacancies
or interstitials

00:25:46.820 --> 00:25:49.160
look like in silicon?

00:25:49.160 --> 00:25:50.660
The reason that
they're a little odd

00:25:50.660 --> 00:25:52.580
is because it's such
an open structure.

00:25:52.580 --> 00:25:54.398
Whereas in a close-packed
metal, a vacancy

00:25:54.398 --> 00:25:56.315
is just taking an atom
out, and interstitials,

00:25:56.315 --> 00:25:59.270
you're just taking putting one
in the interstitial position.

00:25:59.270 --> 00:26:02.840
But because in silicon it's such
a close-packed and covalently

00:26:02.840 --> 00:26:05.047
bonded network, every
time you take an atom out,

00:26:05.047 --> 00:26:07.130
you can actually have quite
a bit of rearrangement

00:26:07.130 --> 00:26:07.922
of the other atoms.

00:26:07.922 --> 00:26:11.180
So it's quite an old
problem, and it's probably

00:26:11.180 --> 00:26:15.890
a problem where computation
has made considerable impact.

00:26:15.890 --> 00:26:19.100
If you have an idea for how the
vacancy or interstitials should

00:26:19.100 --> 00:26:21.770
look like, you can test
it computationally.

00:26:21.770 --> 00:26:24.530
You can calculate its
energy and compare it

00:26:24.530 --> 00:26:30.225
to other potential arrangements.

00:26:30.225 --> 00:26:30.725
OK.

00:26:35.810 --> 00:26:37.610
This is my last
piece of philosophy.

00:26:37.610 --> 00:26:39.500
After that, we'll
start doing real work.

00:26:39.500 --> 00:26:43.370
But this is one that if you
didn't remember anything

00:26:43.370 --> 00:26:45.560
from the class except
one thing, this is

00:26:45.560 --> 00:26:48.500
the one I want you to remember.

00:26:48.500 --> 00:26:53.180
If you do modeling, and
people will come up to you,

00:26:53.180 --> 00:26:55.730
and they will call
it simulation,

00:26:55.730 --> 00:26:58.632
and modeling is not
the same as simulation.

00:26:58.632 --> 00:26:59.840
You should keep that in mind.

00:26:59.840 --> 00:27:01.370
We actually do computation.

00:27:01.370 --> 00:27:02.630
Maybe we do modeling.

00:27:02.630 --> 00:27:04.580
We rarely ever do simulation.

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:07.640
We sometimes do simulation.

00:27:07.640 --> 00:27:12.260
The reason is that
reality is very often

00:27:12.260 --> 00:27:14.760
too complex to simulate.

00:27:14.760 --> 00:27:15.410
OK?

00:27:15.410 --> 00:27:20.480
So rather, what we do is we
isolate parts of reality.

00:27:20.480 --> 00:27:21.170
OK?

00:27:21.170 --> 00:27:23.840
We say, this subset
is important,

00:27:23.840 --> 00:27:25.842
and we do computation on that.

00:27:25.842 --> 00:27:27.800
And what that means is
that you will very often

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:29.420
have to make judgments.

00:27:29.420 --> 00:27:30.320
OK?

00:27:30.320 --> 00:27:33.200
Like if you're going
to study corrosion,

00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:36.050
let's say you're going to study
corrosion of a high strength

00:27:36.050 --> 00:27:37.160
steel.

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:39.910
There is no way in hell
you're going to simulate that,

00:27:39.910 --> 00:27:42.410
because you don't even know
what the relevant variables are.

00:27:42.410 --> 00:27:45.080
You don't even know what the
relevant environments are.

00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:45.620
OK?

00:27:45.620 --> 00:27:47.037
So what you're
going to have to do

00:27:47.037 --> 00:27:50.180
is learn a lot about
the signs of corrosion,

00:27:50.180 --> 00:27:53.780
and take one isolated
element, maybe

00:27:53.780 --> 00:27:56.570
surface attack by
chlorine or something

00:27:56.570 --> 00:28:03.050
like that or hydrogen going
in and locally embrittling

00:28:03.050 --> 00:28:04.370
the material.

00:28:04.370 --> 00:28:07.910
So you will never just take
your high strength steel,

00:28:07.910 --> 00:28:12.230
put it in a computer,
and wait for a long time,

00:28:12.230 --> 00:28:14.870
because you don't even know
what environment to impose

00:28:14.870 --> 00:28:15.890
on that system.

00:28:15.890 --> 00:28:16.940
OK?

00:28:16.940 --> 00:28:21.140
So rarely do we do simulation
to solve complex problems.

00:28:21.140 --> 00:28:22.910
Sometimes, we will
isolate a piece

00:28:22.910 --> 00:28:24.800
and then simulate on
that, but we rarely

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:27.650
simulate the full reality.

00:28:27.650 --> 00:28:29.540
And because of that,
it's really important

00:28:29.540 --> 00:28:32.240
that you know the signs
of the field you work in.

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:32.960
OK?

00:28:32.960 --> 00:28:36.260
You cannot have impact
with computation without

00:28:36.260 --> 00:28:39.440
understanding your field
of application, period,

00:28:39.440 --> 00:28:41.550
because you will never
know what to compute.

00:28:41.550 --> 00:28:42.110
OK?

00:28:42.110 --> 00:28:43.527
So I think if you
want to remember

00:28:43.527 --> 00:28:45.050
one thing, that's the one.

00:28:45.050 --> 00:28:49.020
The hardest part of computing
is knowing what to compute.

00:28:49.020 --> 00:28:50.000
OK?

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:51.830
Everybody can learn
molecular dynamics.

00:28:51.830 --> 00:28:53.720
Everybody can learn
ab initio methods,

00:28:53.720 --> 00:28:59.060
but using them in an intelligent
way becomes the hard part.

00:28:59.060 --> 00:29:01.430
And I like the quote
from Frank Jensen,

00:29:01.430 --> 00:29:03.410
computers don't solve
problems, people

00:29:03.410 --> 00:29:06.770
do, to paraphrase something.

00:29:06.770 --> 00:29:08.060
OK.

00:29:08.060 --> 00:29:09.830
I'm going to skip this.

00:29:09.830 --> 00:29:12.870
I'll let you read this, an
article we put on the web

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:15.650
from James Langer.

00:29:15.650 --> 00:29:17.600
People are trying to
establish computing

00:29:17.600 --> 00:29:19.310
as the third branch of science.

00:29:19.310 --> 00:29:21.920
There's experiment, there's
theory, and there's computing,

00:29:21.920 --> 00:29:24.440
and it's an interesting article.

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:25.100
OK.

00:29:25.100 --> 00:29:27.680
So let me get to
the real science

00:29:27.680 --> 00:29:31.170
that we can do today,
at least a little bit.

00:29:31.170 --> 00:29:36.470
So the first maybe
a few weeks or so,

00:29:36.470 --> 00:29:38.330
we're going to talk
about energy models.

00:29:38.330 --> 00:29:42.830
And the reason we start with
energy models is because I feel

00:29:42.830 --> 00:29:46.220
that, unless you have an
adequate energetic description

00:29:46.220 --> 00:29:49.220
of your material, you really
don't know if what comes out

00:29:49.220 --> 00:29:53.560
of your computations is
actually right or relevant.

00:29:53.560 --> 00:30:02.330
So typically, people distinguish
empirical energy models

00:30:02.330 --> 00:30:04.680
from ab initio or
quantum mechanical,

00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:06.560
so this is what
we sometimes call

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:10.760
ab initio, or first principles.

00:30:17.490 --> 00:30:19.630
In some sense, in empirical
models, all you do

00:30:19.630 --> 00:30:21.460
is you take some
form for the energy,

00:30:21.460 --> 00:30:25.570
and you fit it to any
data you may have,

00:30:25.570 --> 00:30:29.770
and sometimes, that data is
quantum mechanically computed.

00:30:29.770 --> 00:30:33.610
In quantum mechanics, you
leave the fitting aside,

00:30:33.610 --> 00:30:35.950
and you go straight
to just solving

00:30:35.950 --> 00:30:38.230
the Schrodinger equation
for whatever problem

00:30:38.230 --> 00:30:40.170
you're trying to solve.

00:30:40.170 --> 00:30:44.290
And there are methods
in between which

00:30:44.290 --> 00:30:48.640
are semi-empirical which
are essentially quantum

00:30:48.640 --> 00:30:53.340
mechanical in form but
empirical in the parameters.

00:30:53.340 --> 00:30:56.710
Essentially tied binding
fits into these, things

00:30:56.710 --> 00:30:59.035
that the chemists often
do, like MINDO and INDO.

00:30:59.035 --> 00:31:01.930
So these are effectively,
you could think of them

00:31:01.930 --> 00:31:06.820
as parameterized Schrodinger
equations almost,

00:31:06.820 --> 00:31:09.610
where the overlap integrals
between wave functions

00:31:09.610 --> 00:31:12.370
are not computed but
are parameterized.

00:31:12.370 --> 00:31:15.910
So you save a lot of time.

00:31:15.910 --> 00:31:19.540
Personally, I believe that
that middlefield is losing

00:31:19.540 --> 00:31:22.190
in importance considerably.

00:31:22.190 --> 00:31:24.290
I think if we'd given
this class 10 years ago,

00:31:24.290 --> 00:31:26.410
we would have talked
a lot about that.

00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:28.450
Because people see
that as a way of like,

00:31:28.450 --> 00:31:31.240
well, it's much
faster than ab initio,

00:31:31.240 --> 00:31:33.920
but you keep some of
the accuracy of it.

00:31:33.920 --> 00:31:37.750
I think that's less and
less true these days.

00:31:37.750 --> 00:31:41.290
You don't keep as much accuracy
as you usually want to,

00:31:41.290 --> 00:31:43.450
and it's not as
much faster anymore.

00:31:43.450 --> 00:31:45.730
So while there are
obviously still problems

00:31:45.730 --> 00:31:49.690
where this is important,
more and more people

00:31:49.690 --> 00:31:52.450
just do the ab initio, period.

00:31:52.450 --> 00:31:54.980
Computers are cheap these days.

00:31:54.980 --> 00:31:57.130
The reason we teach you
about empirical models

00:31:57.130 --> 00:31:59.480
is because, first of
all, you will encounter,

00:31:59.480 --> 00:32:02.350
and if you're going to do
really, really large problems,

00:32:02.350 --> 00:32:05.170
they can be quite useful.

00:32:05.170 --> 00:32:08.650
And also, they are really great
handle I find to teach you some

00:32:08.650 --> 00:32:12.070
of the essential energy physics
that you need to deal with when

00:32:12.070 --> 00:32:15.220
studying different materials,
and so that's why I spend 2,

00:32:15.220 --> 00:32:18.475
2 1/2 lectures on
empirical models.

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:21.340
OK.

00:32:26.940 --> 00:32:29.130
And so obviously, keep
the obviously in mind,

00:32:29.130 --> 00:32:31.140
that if you work
with potentials,

00:32:31.140 --> 00:32:33.660
you have no information
about electrons.

00:32:33.660 --> 00:32:36.660
You just have energies as
a function of position.

00:32:36.660 --> 00:32:39.433
If you work with semi-empirical
and quantum mechanics,

00:32:39.433 --> 00:32:40.725
you also have more information.

00:32:40.725 --> 00:32:43.950
You know something about
the electronic structure

00:32:43.950 --> 00:32:45.120
of the material.

00:32:45.120 --> 00:32:49.080
Which one is best, I think
that's an irrelevant question,

00:32:49.080 --> 00:32:50.580
depends what you can afford.

00:32:50.580 --> 00:32:51.080
OK.

00:33:03.910 --> 00:33:08.680
So essentially,
what you want if you

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:10.667
want to do an empirical
modeling method

00:33:10.667 --> 00:33:13.000
is that you want to have the
energy as a function of all

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.700
the nuclear coordinates.

00:33:15.700 --> 00:33:18.430
That already itself
implies an assumption,

00:33:18.430 --> 00:33:20.950
because the energy is actually
a function of the nuclear

00:33:20.950 --> 00:33:23.260
and the electronic coordinates.

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:26.830
Typically, what we do
is we variationally

00:33:26.830 --> 00:33:29.830
remove the electronic
coordinates,

00:33:29.830 --> 00:33:31.630
and that's essentially
what's called

00:33:31.630 --> 00:33:33.610
the Born-Oppenheimer
approximation.

00:33:33.610 --> 00:33:35.170
If you think if
your atom-- if you

00:33:35.170 --> 00:33:37.130
have a bunch of atoms together.

00:33:37.130 --> 00:33:42.850
So you have a set of coordinates
that describe the positions.

00:33:47.350 --> 00:33:51.940
People think that the energy
is uniquely determined

00:33:51.940 --> 00:33:56.260
by that set of coordinates,
but that's actually not true.

00:33:56.260 --> 00:34:01.000
Because you have electronic
states, and in many cases,

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:04.390
for a given state
of the nuclei, you

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:07.090
can have multiple
electronic states.

00:34:07.090 --> 00:34:08.330
OK?

00:34:08.330 --> 00:34:10.960
There'll be a ground state, but
you can be in excited states

00:34:10.960 --> 00:34:12.429
as well.

00:34:12.429 --> 00:34:15.550
What the Born-Oppenheimer
approximation essentially

00:34:15.550 --> 00:34:19.570
assumes is that, for any
set of nuclear coordinates,

00:34:19.570 --> 00:34:23.090
you are always in the
electronic ground state.

00:34:23.090 --> 00:34:27.850
So ER is derived from
ER psi by essentially

00:34:27.850 --> 00:34:31.969
variationally removing psi
by minimizing over psi.

00:34:31.969 --> 00:34:33.070
OK?

00:34:33.070 --> 00:34:36.969
So what's the physical
implementation here?

00:34:41.258 --> 00:34:43.780
If you're in a
stationary configuration,

00:34:43.780 --> 00:34:46.540
and you wait long enough,
this is probably OK.

00:34:46.540 --> 00:34:49.960
If your atoms sit there
frozen in some position,

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:51.760
if you wait long
enough, the electrons

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:54.820
will go to the ground state,
especially when you're

00:34:54.820 --> 00:34:57.040
at 0 temperature.

00:34:57.040 --> 00:35:01.372
Where is can wreak havoc is
in certain molds of dynamics,

00:35:01.372 --> 00:35:02.830
because what you're
really assuming

00:35:02.830 --> 00:35:07.120
is that, if you move your
atoms, your electrons follow

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:09.110
infinitely fast.

00:35:09.110 --> 00:35:09.620
OK?

00:35:09.620 --> 00:35:12.980
Because if you move
the atom a little bit,

00:35:12.980 --> 00:35:15.620
the energy change
is the energy change

00:35:15.620 --> 00:35:18.440
when the electrons relax
immediately to the ground

00:35:18.440 --> 00:35:20.090
state, as you move the atoms.

00:35:20.090 --> 00:35:22.070
OK?

00:35:22.070 --> 00:35:24.450
That's essentially the
Born-Oppenheimer approximation.

00:35:24.450 --> 00:35:25.992
So when is this not
going to be true?

00:35:29.270 --> 00:35:31.130
It's when the atoms
move really fast,

00:35:31.130 --> 00:35:34.280
or the electrons
move really slow,

00:35:34.280 --> 00:35:36.092
and there are cases like that.

00:35:36.092 --> 00:35:37.550
This is one of
these approximations

00:35:37.550 --> 00:35:39.980
that we want to believe is
always true, because it's

00:35:39.980 --> 00:35:41.510
very hard to do anything else.

00:35:41.510 --> 00:35:44.210
So we kind of kid
ourselves, because it's

00:35:44.210 --> 00:35:46.520
very hard to verify as well.

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:51.020
But there are long-lived
excited states in materials.

00:35:51.020 --> 00:35:53.405
There are defects in
semiconductors, for example,

00:35:53.405 --> 00:35:56.540
EL2 in gallium arsenide
was a famous one

00:35:56.540 --> 00:35:58.970
that has very long-lived
excited states, where

00:35:58.970 --> 00:36:01.640
there are essentially two
Born-Oppenheimer surfaces.

00:36:01.640 --> 00:36:04.400
Let's call one the
ground state one,

00:36:04.400 --> 00:36:07.100
and then there's another one
that's the excited state one.

00:36:07.100 --> 00:36:09.440
And the interesting
thing was they gave you

00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:11.580
different nuclear coordinates.

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:13.980
So if you minimized it under
one equipotential surface

00:36:13.980 --> 00:36:15.522
and under the other
one, you ended up

00:36:15.522 --> 00:36:17.240
in a different
nuclear configuration.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:19.410
So you see then,
you have a problem.

00:36:19.410 --> 00:36:23.330
You can find the lowest energy
configuration of the nuclei,

00:36:23.330 --> 00:36:25.700
unless you know what
the electrons do.

00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:27.480
So you now have a
coupled problem.

00:36:27.480 --> 00:36:28.850
OK?

00:36:28.850 --> 00:36:31.790
So that's a
non-obvious violation

00:36:31.790 --> 00:36:34.130
of the Born-Oppenheimer
approximation.

00:36:34.130 --> 00:36:38.990
In fast dynamics, things
that move fast, like protons.

00:36:38.990 --> 00:36:42.470
The lightest nucleus or
protons can move very fast,

00:36:42.470 --> 00:36:45.680
and in some cases, the electrons
won't follow fast enough.

00:36:45.680 --> 00:36:50.690
In insulators, let's say
you studied diffusion

00:36:50.690 --> 00:36:53.880
of charged ions in insulators.

00:36:53.880 --> 00:36:56.070
OK?

00:36:56.070 --> 00:36:57.560
So I work on battery materials.

00:36:57.560 --> 00:37:00.020
It's all about lithium
plus diffusion,

00:37:00.020 --> 00:37:01.430
lithium ions diffuse.

00:37:01.430 --> 00:37:05.180
Well, if the ion diffuses--
if the iron hops very fast,

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:07.460
but I'm in an insulator,
maybe the electron

00:37:07.460 --> 00:37:09.510
won't follow fast enough.

00:37:09.510 --> 00:37:10.010
OK?

00:37:10.010 --> 00:37:13.320
So I'm going away from the
Born-Oppenheimer surface there.

00:37:13.320 --> 00:37:13.820
OK?

00:37:13.820 --> 00:37:16.748
So this problem actually
appears more than you think.

00:37:16.748 --> 00:37:18.790
It's just that we don't
know how to deal with it.

00:37:18.790 --> 00:37:23.840
So we like, shush, remove
it from our thoughts.

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:26.900
The other obvious violation
of Born-Oppenheimer

00:37:26.900 --> 00:37:31.160
is when you're at
nonzero temperature.

00:37:31.160 --> 00:37:33.110
When you're at
nonzero temperature,

00:37:33.110 --> 00:37:37.670
you have a finite probability
to actually occupy

00:37:37.670 --> 00:37:41.120
the higher level electronic
citations, so the higher energy

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:43.010
electronics states.

00:37:43.010 --> 00:37:45.200
That's not a really big problem.

00:37:45.200 --> 00:37:48.020
It is technically a violation
of the Born-Oppenheimer

00:37:48.020 --> 00:37:51.410
approximation, but essentially,
it's easy to solve.

00:37:51.410 --> 00:37:54.230
You can replace this minimum.

00:37:54.230 --> 00:37:57.500
So minimizing it
by statistically

00:37:57.500 --> 00:38:00.740
averaging over the right
levels by literally

00:38:00.740 --> 00:38:04.490
doing a statistical weighting
of how the levels are populated.

00:38:04.490 --> 00:38:06.950
Then, they do a statistical
mechanics approach,

00:38:06.950 --> 00:38:09.343
and we'll talk much
more about these things

00:38:09.343 --> 00:38:10.760
when we talk about
coarse graining

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:14.090
methods in the later
part of the course.

00:38:14.090 --> 00:38:19.140
So temperature isn't a big
deal for Born-Oppenheimer.

00:38:19.140 --> 00:38:19.640
OK.

00:38:22.480 --> 00:38:28.150
So here's what we're
going to do on potentials.

00:38:28.150 --> 00:38:30.910
There are as many different
potentials as there are people.

00:38:30.910 --> 00:38:32.410
Everybody has
their favorite one.

00:38:32.410 --> 00:38:34.270
So we're going to
pick and choose,

00:38:34.270 --> 00:38:36.190
and I'm mainly going
to pick and choose

00:38:36.190 --> 00:38:40.790
based on the materials physics
I can teach you with them.

00:38:40.790 --> 00:38:43.750
So we're going to talk
about a few particular forms

00:38:43.750 --> 00:38:47.860
and the physical limitations
that they introduce,

00:38:47.860 --> 00:38:50.530
and I'm going to start
with pair potentials,

00:38:50.530 --> 00:38:52.450
because they're the obvious one.

00:38:52.450 --> 00:38:55.460
That'll be today, and then
that'll obviously lead us,

00:38:55.460 --> 00:38:58.690
the failures of those will lead
us into many body potentials

00:38:58.690 --> 00:39:00.730
and pair functionals.

00:39:00.730 --> 00:39:02.380
This one will be
particularly relevant

00:39:02.380 --> 00:39:11.160
for covalent delocalized
materials, like metals,

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:14.510
and this is for delocalized--

00:39:14.510 --> 00:39:15.440
sorry.

00:39:15.440 --> 00:39:17.420
Sorry, covalent localized.

00:39:21.770 --> 00:39:24.470
So we're mainly going to talk
about the form of these things.

00:39:24.470 --> 00:39:25.887
I'm not going to
spend a whole lot

00:39:25.887 --> 00:39:31.730
of time talking about the
detailed parameters you put in.

00:39:31.730 --> 00:39:32.230
OK.

00:39:39.640 --> 00:39:42.700
So here's pair potentials.

00:39:42.700 --> 00:39:44.530
Obviously, what are
you really saying

00:39:44.530 --> 00:39:46.780
when you use pair potentials
to model something?

00:39:46.780 --> 00:39:49.810
You're saying that, if I have
a bunch of atoms together,

00:39:49.810 --> 00:39:54.340
I can sum their energy
from pairwise interactions.

00:39:54.340 --> 00:39:58.860
So you're saying that this
interaction between these two

00:39:58.860 --> 00:40:01.980
atoms has nothing to do with
whether this atom or that atom

00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:02.610
is present.

00:40:02.610 --> 00:40:05.340
That's essentially the
physics of what you're saying.

00:40:05.340 --> 00:40:07.320
You're summing the energy.

00:40:07.320 --> 00:40:11.220
In some cases, you take a
constant, and then simply

00:40:11.220 --> 00:40:15.350
a sum of interaction
potentials that only

00:40:15.350 --> 00:40:20.741
depend on the distance
between two atoms.

00:40:20.741 --> 00:40:24.350
Pair potentials pretty much
always have the same form.

00:40:24.350 --> 00:40:32.930
They are attractive at
intermediate to long distance,

00:40:32.930 --> 00:40:34.850
and they are repulsive
at short distance.

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:39.810
And they have to be
repulsive at short distance,

00:40:39.810 --> 00:40:42.640
because otherwise, your
system collapses into itself.

