00:41:09.310 --> 00:41:14.290
Every lecture will have
something like that.

00:41:14.290 --> 00:41:15.550
Something odd happens.

00:41:15.550 --> 00:41:16.580
We do it deliberately.

00:41:16.580 --> 00:41:18.760
No.

00:41:18.760 --> 00:41:20.770
One issue, practical
issue with potentials,

00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:23.480
is that you have
to truncate them.

00:41:23.480 --> 00:41:24.070
OK?

00:41:24.070 --> 00:41:27.010
Because you want to
keep this pairwise

00:41:27.010 --> 00:41:28.900
distance not out to infinity.

00:41:28.900 --> 00:41:30.880
Most potential is just
the form they have.

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:34.750
They slowly decay, and people
do all kinds of tricks.

00:41:34.750 --> 00:41:37.150
The problem is if
you say, I'm only

00:41:37.150 --> 00:41:40.450
going to truncate
up to here, that you

00:41:40.450 --> 00:41:42.850
have this discontinuity.

00:41:42.850 --> 00:41:44.770
Let me see if I can
make a wide slide,

00:41:44.770 --> 00:41:46.814
if I remember how to do this.

00:41:46.814 --> 00:41:49.290
Ah, magic.

00:41:49.290 --> 00:41:51.890
OK.

00:41:51.890 --> 00:41:55.610
So let's say I truncate
the potential here

00:41:55.610 --> 00:41:56.600
at this distance.

00:41:56.600 --> 00:41:58.850
Then essentially, my potential
really looks like this.

00:42:02.710 --> 00:42:06.120
I have this discontinuity in
it which is not very good.

00:42:06.120 --> 00:42:11.220
Because whenever atoms move
in and out of this range,

00:42:11.220 --> 00:42:14.400
they actually have a
strong energy jump,

00:42:14.400 --> 00:42:16.360
as they move in and
out of that range.

00:42:16.360 --> 00:42:17.740
So people do all
kinds of tricks.

00:42:17.740 --> 00:42:23.310
You can smooth this, like
attach some spline to it that

00:42:23.310 --> 00:42:26.970
smooths this out to zero.

00:42:26.970 --> 00:42:29.742
Sometimes, you want
to have literally zero

00:42:29.742 --> 00:42:30.450
at some distance.

00:42:30.450 --> 00:42:32.180
Sometimes, you also
like zero derivative,

00:42:32.180 --> 00:42:34.140
so you have continuous forces.

00:42:34.140 --> 00:42:36.300
Some people use
shifted potentials

00:42:36.300 --> 00:42:38.040
which is kind of cute.

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:42.690
If you know that this has some
value, let's say epsilon here,

00:42:42.690 --> 00:42:47.180
you just shift the
potential up by epsilon.

00:42:47.180 --> 00:42:49.400
So now, it's zero
at your cutoff,

00:42:49.400 --> 00:42:50.900
but of course, the
force would still

00:42:50.900 --> 00:42:54.908
be discontinuous, because the
force would be the derivative.

00:42:57.490 --> 00:42:57.990
OK.

00:43:06.080 --> 00:43:09.170
The most simple potential form
that you'll sometimes see used

00:43:09.170 --> 00:43:12.800
is the Lennard-Jones
potential which

00:43:12.800 --> 00:43:17.210
has an R to the 6th which
is the attractive part.

00:43:17.210 --> 00:43:17.710
OK?

00:43:20.307 --> 00:43:21.890
That gives you the
attractions and has

00:43:21.890 --> 00:43:24.740
the negative sign in front,
and the R to the 12th

00:43:24.740 --> 00:43:26.000
which gives you the repulsion.

00:43:34.190 --> 00:43:38.700
The R to the 6th
term can actually

00:43:38.700 --> 00:43:40.890
be physically justified.

00:43:40.890 --> 00:43:45.030
It comes from the interaction
between fluctuating dipoles.

00:43:45.030 --> 00:43:48.000
If you have an atom here with
its electron cloud and an atom

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.460
here, and if these
are inert atoms,

00:43:50.460 --> 00:43:54.300
so with filled electron shell,
so there's no covalent bonding

00:43:54.300 --> 00:43:55.540
going on with them.

00:43:55.540 --> 00:43:59.190
So these are either ions
with a filled shell,

00:43:59.190 --> 00:44:01.830
or they're noble gases.

00:44:01.830 --> 00:44:05.400
Then, there is no direct
covalent interaction,

00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:07.890
so the interaction you get
is from fluctuating dipoles.

00:44:07.890 --> 00:44:12.180
So at some point,
there's a dipole

00:44:12.180 --> 00:44:15.390
that, just from fluctuations,
that sets up here,

00:44:15.390 --> 00:44:22.040
and that will induce a dipole
in the other electron cloud.

00:44:22.040 --> 00:44:26.770
And so the interaction
between these dipoles

00:44:26.770 --> 00:44:30.310
and these dipoles, if
you actually look at it,

00:44:30.310 --> 00:44:31.990
gives you an R to the 6th.

00:44:31.990 --> 00:44:35.860
So this piece is
physically justifiable,

00:44:35.860 --> 00:44:38.752
and that's where
Lennard-Jones got it from.

00:44:38.752 --> 00:44:40.210
It's essentially
the form of what's

00:44:40.210 --> 00:44:42.730
called a Van der Waals
interaction which

00:44:42.730 --> 00:44:46.060
is the interaction
between inner shells.

00:44:46.060 --> 00:44:49.266
So where does the R to the
12th come from, you think?

00:44:53.390 --> 00:44:57.540
Obviously, you need
something steep to get that.

00:44:57.540 --> 00:44:59.660
Otherwise, the ions
fly into each other.

00:44:59.660 --> 00:45:02.060
You need this steep
repulsive part

00:45:02.060 --> 00:45:04.530
when the ions come
very close together,

00:45:04.530 --> 00:45:07.940
and essentially what the physics
of it is the Pauli repulsion.

00:45:07.940 --> 00:45:10.760
As the electron clouds come
into each other, remember,

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:14.280
the electrons cannot occupy
exactly the same quantum state.

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:16.280
And so as you bring
them closer, you're

00:45:16.280 --> 00:45:18.950
almost forcing them to occupy
the same quantum state,

00:45:18.950 --> 00:45:20.180
but why R to the 12th?

00:45:24.370 --> 00:45:28.390
It's really because it's
the square of R to the 6th.

00:45:28.390 --> 00:45:30.220
There is no physical
justification

00:45:30.220 --> 00:45:33.010
for R to the 12th.

00:45:33.010 --> 00:45:34.750
Lennard-Jones used
it, because it

00:45:34.750 --> 00:45:38.860
makes the math of some things
you want to do with it easy,

00:45:38.860 --> 00:45:41.350
because it's the
square of R to the 6th.

00:45:41.350 --> 00:45:46.060
So if you like R or the 10th,
R to the 14th, R to the 16th,

00:45:46.060 --> 00:45:48.672
go ahead.

00:45:48.672 --> 00:45:50.630
People always take the
Lennard-Jones potential,

00:45:50.630 --> 00:45:52.270
because it's there.

00:45:52.270 --> 00:45:55.630
And like I said, the R to
the 6th, I grant you that.

00:45:55.630 --> 00:45:56.950
Maybe you should keep that.

00:45:56.950 --> 00:45:58.812
That is a true Van
der Waals interaction,

00:45:58.812 --> 00:46:00.520
but the R to the 12th,
there is no reason

00:46:00.520 --> 00:46:02.350
that it should be R to the 12th.

00:46:02.350 --> 00:46:02.920
OK?

00:46:02.920 --> 00:46:05.900
Anything, sometimes you actually
want steeper potentials,

00:46:05.900 --> 00:46:08.290
so you make it like R to the
20 or something or whatever.

00:46:11.350 --> 00:46:12.490
OK.

00:46:12.490 --> 00:46:15.280
The other thing is that
people use the Lennard-Jones

00:46:15.280 --> 00:46:18.160
potentials to attract
atoms together

00:46:18.160 --> 00:46:22.090
that has nothing to do with
Van der Waals interaction,

00:46:22.090 --> 00:46:24.040
to actually look at
things that almost

00:46:24.040 --> 00:46:26.032
have some covalent interaction.

00:46:26.032 --> 00:46:27.490
And then there's
actually no reason

00:46:27.490 --> 00:46:29.680
to keep the R of the 6th.

00:46:29.680 --> 00:46:30.250
OK?

00:46:30.250 --> 00:46:31.667
Because the R to
the 6th is really

00:46:31.667 --> 00:46:36.760
only physically justifiable
for Van der Waals terms.

00:46:36.760 --> 00:46:39.180
OK.

00:46:39.180 --> 00:46:40.930
The interesting thing
about Lennard-Jones,

00:46:40.930 --> 00:46:42.472
it's actually the
simplest potential,

00:46:42.472 --> 00:46:45.400
because it only
has two parameters.

00:46:45.400 --> 00:46:48.190
There's essentially A and
B, or if you renormalize

00:46:48.190 --> 00:46:52.500
the potential, there's
an energy scale,

00:46:52.500 --> 00:46:54.105
and there's a length scale.

00:46:54.105 --> 00:46:56.430
So you see, if you
write it in this form,

00:46:56.430 --> 00:46:59.250
you see that the
potential is in units

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:02.870
of epsilon, and the
length, or the sigma which

00:47:02.870 --> 00:47:04.110
is the distance--

00:47:04.110 --> 00:47:07.830
I'm sorry, the R which is the
distance is in units of sigma.

00:47:07.830 --> 00:47:08.760
OK?

00:47:08.760 --> 00:47:11.580
So what that means is
that there's essentially

00:47:11.580 --> 00:47:15.070
only one Lennard-Jones
system in the world.

00:47:15.070 --> 00:47:17.880
You will see tabulated
Lennard-Jones parameters

00:47:17.880 --> 00:47:22.110
for a lot of materials,
but if you think of it,

00:47:22.110 --> 00:47:24.690
the energy scale
of your potential

00:47:24.690 --> 00:47:28.170
sets the temperature
scale of the system.

00:47:28.170 --> 00:47:33.210
And the length scale sets
the volume or therefore

00:47:33.210 --> 00:47:35.080
the pressure scale.

00:47:35.080 --> 00:47:37.080
So if you take one
Lennard-Jones system

00:47:37.080 --> 00:47:41.280
at a given temperature
and pressure,

00:47:41.280 --> 00:47:44.970
that will always be the
same as a Lennard-Jones

00:47:44.970 --> 00:47:47.340
system without the parameters
but at another temperature

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:48.280
and pressure.

00:47:48.280 --> 00:47:50.850
So there's a unique
transformation

00:47:50.850 --> 00:47:52.590
going between all
Lennard-Jones systems.

00:47:52.590 --> 00:47:53.418
Yes, sir.

00:47:53.418 --> 00:47:56.764
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:59.160 --> 00:47:59.790
PROFESSOR: No.

00:47:59.790 --> 00:48:04.250
Sometimes, people leave
out that factor of 2.

00:48:04.250 --> 00:48:04.900
I'm sorry?

00:48:04.900 --> 00:48:08.246
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:12.240 --> 00:48:13.240
PROFESSOR: I'm not sure.

00:48:13.240 --> 00:48:17.800
I think the reason
the factor 2 is there,

00:48:17.800 --> 00:48:20.050
if you differentiate
it, and that way you

00:48:20.050 --> 00:48:22.480
find the minimum is
exactly at sigma.

00:48:22.480 --> 00:48:22.980
OK?

00:48:22.980 --> 00:48:26.030
Because if you differentiate
the 12, you get a factor of 12.

00:48:26.030 --> 00:48:30.190
If you differentiate
the 6, you get a 6.

00:48:30.190 --> 00:48:35.110
You could leave 2 out, but
then sigma is not the value

00:48:35.110 --> 00:48:37.190
where the potential is minimum.

00:48:37.190 --> 00:48:42.850
That's the reason people put
sigma there, because I think--

00:48:42.850 --> 00:48:46.630
I may be wrong-- but I think
in this form, this is sigma.

00:48:46.630 --> 00:48:47.150
OK?

00:48:47.150 --> 00:48:50.300
And I actually think
that this is epsilon,

00:48:50.300 --> 00:48:51.590
but I should verify that.

00:48:55.860 --> 00:48:57.880
So there is essentially
only one Lennard-Jones.

00:48:57.880 --> 00:48:58.963
Ah, there's Lennard-Jones.

00:48:58.963 --> 00:49:01.640
I forgot his picture.

00:49:01.640 --> 00:49:06.140
I think it's sir now, Sir
Lennard-Jones, I think.

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:06.640
OK.

00:49:18.160 --> 00:49:21.760
Usually, two parameters is
just not enough in a potential,

00:49:21.760 --> 00:49:26.470
and the reason is
that usually you

00:49:26.470 --> 00:49:31.100
want to mimic at least three
properties of a material.

00:49:31.100 --> 00:49:35.410
Its length scale which is its
largest parameter, its energy

00:49:35.410 --> 00:49:38.350
scale which you can think of
as its cohesive energy which

00:49:38.350 --> 00:49:40.690
is the potential
depth, but you also

00:49:40.690 --> 00:49:43.780
want to get its
elasticity right.

00:49:43.780 --> 00:49:44.530
OK?

00:49:44.530 --> 00:49:47.890
And so that's three
fundamental properties

00:49:47.890 --> 00:49:50.290
to get right, because
its elasticity tells you

00:49:50.290 --> 00:49:54.640
its response to
any perturbations.

00:49:54.640 --> 00:49:57.370
And the problem is that a
Lennard-Jones potential only

00:49:57.370 --> 00:49:58.660
has two parameters.

00:49:58.660 --> 00:50:01.340
You cannot fit three
things with two parameters.

00:50:01.340 --> 00:50:04.480
So most people will go to
things with three parameters,

00:50:04.480 --> 00:50:08.140
usually, so they can get
these three things right.

00:50:08.140 --> 00:50:12.540
And one classic is
a Morse potential

00:50:12.540 --> 00:50:15.530
which has D which
sets the energy scale,

00:50:15.530 --> 00:50:20.000
R0 which sets the length
scale, and alpha which

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:21.470
sets the elasticity scale.

00:50:21.470 --> 00:50:24.440
Because you can see
alpha sets in some sense

00:50:24.440 --> 00:50:26.090
the curvature of the potential.

00:50:26.090 --> 00:50:29.810
It's what you multiply with
the distance differential.

00:50:29.810 --> 00:50:30.530
OK?

00:50:30.530 --> 00:50:33.695
So alpha will be a measure
of the elastic behavior.

00:50:37.070 --> 00:50:40.100
In particular, in oxides,
the form that's most popular

00:50:40.100 --> 00:50:44.210
is what's called a Born-Mayor
or a Buckingham potential which

00:50:44.210 --> 00:50:48.700
is essentially a decaying
exponential, a Van der Waals

00:50:48.700 --> 00:50:52.900
term, and then the second
order term in Van der Waals

00:50:52.900 --> 00:50:56.560
perturbation theory which is
the R of the 8th parameter.

00:51:02.710 --> 00:51:04.390
The weird thing
about this potential

00:51:04.390 --> 00:51:06.220
that you have to be
somewhat careful about

00:51:06.220 --> 00:51:10.630
is that it diverges at short
distances if you plot it.

00:51:13.600 --> 00:51:17.140
If you plot the
exponential, that

00:51:17.140 --> 00:51:21.250
goes to a finite value
of A when R is 0.

00:51:21.250 --> 00:51:24.700
So the exponential to
something like this,

00:51:24.700 --> 00:51:27.000
and this is A-- it's actually
a lot steeper in reality.

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:31.333
Typically, A is very large, but
these terms, these R to the 6th

00:51:31.333 --> 00:51:32.250
and the R to the 8th--

00:51:32.250 --> 00:51:35.340
1 over R to the 6th and 1 over
R to the 8th diverge and R

00:51:35.340 --> 00:51:36.480
goes to 0.

00:51:36.480 --> 00:51:38.580
So they, on the other
hand, look like this, where

00:51:38.580 --> 00:51:41.710
this goes to minus infinity.

00:51:41.710 --> 00:51:46.740
So when you add the two up,
you get something like this.

00:51:49.340 --> 00:51:49.840
I'm sorry.

00:51:49.840 --> 00:51:52.730
This is supposed to go down.

00:51:52.730 --> 00:51:57.300
So if you look only up to here,
this potential looks fine.

00:51:57.300 --> 00:52:01.190
But if you go past it, if you
in some sense go into the core,

00:52:01.190 --> 00:52:07.100
the potential diverges, and
you may think that's silly.

00:52:07.100 --> 00:52:08.990
You never go there,
but you sometimes

00:52:08.990 --> 00:52:12.020
do because of numerical issues.

00:52:12.020 --> 00:52:15.440
Sometimes, what happens
in say a simulation is

00:52:15.440 --> 00:52:18.560
that, when you start--

00:52:18.560 --> 00:52:20.690
let's say you do something
molecular dynamics which

00:52:20.690 --> 00:52:24.860
is essentially evolving atoms
according to their force.

00:52:24.860 --> 00:52:28.560
You may start in a configuration
very far from equilibrium.

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:32.660
So in the initial steps, atoms
move with tremendous force,

00:52:32.660 --> 00:52:35.480
and so because of that, they
can literally just overshoot

00:52:35.480 --> 00:52:37.190
and shoot into each other.

00:52:37.190 --> 00:52:39.050
And what you see
is that actually

00:52:39.050 --> 00:52:41.570
the state with two atoms
on top of each other

00:52:41.570 --> 00:52:45.150
is a highly bonded state
in this kind of potential.

00:52:45.150 --> 00:52:46.490
So you will never escape it.

00:52:46.490 --> 00:52:49.220
You were really just put
atoms on top of each other.

00:52:49.220 --> 00:52:51.800
And trust me, if you work
with Born-Mayer potentials,

00:52:51.800 --> 00:52:53.750
and you're not careful,
you will see that.

00:52:53.750 --> 00:52:55.760
You will see atoms sitting
on top of each other,

00:52:55.760 --> 00:52:57.170
exactly because of this problem.

00:52:59.920 --> 00:53:01.250
OK.

00:53:01.250 --> 00:53:04.422
I got some Morse potential
parameters out of a book.

00:53:04.422 --> 00:53:05.630
It's probably rather useless.

00:53:05.630 --> 00:53:07.400
Nobody would use this
anymore for metals

00:53:07.400 --> 00:53:10.550
to be honest, because I'll
show you a bit later why.

00:53:10.550 --> 00:53:12.780
These pair potentials are
not very good for metals.

00:53:12.780 --> 00:53:13.556
Yes.

00:53:13.556 --> 00:53:16.958
