00:53:37.370 --> 00:53:37.870
you.

00:53:42.430 --> 00:53:44.020
I wanted to show
you the difference

00:53:44.020 --> 00:53:49.340
between a few potentials
for a specific bond.

00:53:49.340 --> 00:53:54.190
This is the CH bond in
methane, and so they're all

00:53:54.190 --> 00:54:00.520
fitted to have the same bonding
energy and the same modulus.

00:54:00.520 --> 00:54:02.860
So the same bond distance,
the same bonding energy,

00:54:02.860 --> 00:54:06.460
and same modulus, and
this is the exact curve

00:54:06.460 --> 00:54:09.970
in the solid line.

00:54:09.970 --> 00:54:13.810
The dash dash dotted
is the Morse potential.

00:54:13.810 --> 00:54:17.770
That's actually the one that's
very close to the exact line.

00:54:21.240 --> 00:54:22.770
Let's see if I get this right.

00:54:22.770 --> 00:54:25.480
This is just a
harmonic potential.

00:54:25.480 --> 00:54:28.380
So this is something
like what they call P2.

00:54:28.380 --> 00:54:34.200
This is sort of K times
delta R-squared, where

00:54:34.200 --> 00:54:36.500
delta R is the distance
away from the equilibrium

00:54:36.500 --> 00:54:40.960
bound in geometry, and P4
is a 4th order polynomial.

00:54:40.960 --> 00:54:46.140
So that would be K
plus let's say L delta

00:54:46.140 --> 00:54:49.230
R cubed to the 4th power.

00:54:49.230 --> 00:54:50.910
And I think the
interesting thing

00:54:50.910 --> 00:54:53.130
is that near the minimum
they all look the same.

00:54:53.130 --> 00:54:54.480
They pretty much have to.

00:54:54.480 --> 00:54:57.030
They have the same
position in the minimum,

00:54:57.030 --> 00:54:59.150
and they have the
same curvature.

00:54:59.150 --> 00:55:00.870
OK?

00:55:00.870 --> 00:55:02.880
So if you're only
going to be looking

00:55:02.880 --> 00:55:06.540
at very short displacements
around the equilibrium,

00:55:06.540 --> 00:55:09.357
actually just your
quadratic is fine,

00:55:09.357 --> 00:55:10.440
and you'll see that often.

00:55:10.440 --> 00:55:13.110
People who model
small deformations

00:55:13.110 --> 00:55:14.670
in organic systems
in polymers and so

00:55:14.670 --> 00:55:17.030
will often just use
spring models, essentially

00:55:17.030 --> 00:55:18.640
a harmonic potential.

00:55:18.640 --> 00:55:22.200
So to decide what
potential you need,

00:55:22.200 --> 00:55:24.000
you should think
about how far you want

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:26.010
to go away from equilibrium.

00:55:26.010 --> 00:55:28.440
If you go very far away
from equilibrium, obviously,

00:55:28.440 --> 00:55:31.980
this Morse potential
does a fine job.

00:55:31.980 --> 00:55:34.080
If you stay very
close to equilibrium,

00:55:34.080 --> 00:55:35.790
you may not want to
put in that effort.

00:55:35.790 --> 00:55:39.240
It's much easier to
work with a spring model

00:55:39.240 --> 00:55:41.610
than to actually work
with a Morse potential.

00:55:41.610 --> 00:55:44.413
It's much faster to
evaluate a quadratic.

00:55:50.650 --> 00:55:53.440
I always thought I should
put a section in my lectures

00:55:53.440 --> 00:55:58.000
on how to fit potentials, and
every time, I look up papers,

00:55:58.000 --> 00:55:59.980
and I can never find
anything systematic.

00:55:59.980 --> 00:56:02.320
So I think the rule
is you fit to anything

00:56:02.320 --> 00:56:04.810
you can get your hands on.

00:56:04.810 --> 00:56:09.190
And as we'll point out
later more carefully,

00:56:09.190 --> 00:56:12.730
since potentials only
have a limited region

00:56:12.730 --> 00:56:14.710
of applicability,
you want to fit

00:56:14.710 --> 00:56:16.420
as close as possible
to the things

00:56:16.420 --> 00:56:18.560
you're going to calculate,
to the environment

00:56:18.560 --> 00:56:20.620
you're going to calculate,
but so in theory, that

00:56:20.620 --> 00:56:22.030
could be anything.

00:56:22.030 --> 00:56:23.800
There's the obvious candidates.

00:56:23.800 --> 00:56:26.200
You always want to get the
length scale and the energy

00:56:26.200 --> 00:56:29.360
scale pretty much right and
the stiffness, here sort

00:56:29.360 --> 00:56:31.510
of obvious.

00:56:31.510 --> 00:56:36.790
In some cases, you want to get
low symmetry environment right.

00:56:36.790 --> 00:56:41.380
So if you only fit to
crystal structures,

00:56:41.380 --> 00:56:45.310
you may have very poor
reproduction of low symmetry

00:56:45.310 --> 00:56:51.110
things, like surface energies
or what goes on in a liquid.

00:56:51.110 --> 00:56:53.788
And so in some cases, people
explicitly fit to that.

00:56:53.788 --> 00:56:55.330
I wouldn't worry
too much about this.

00:56:55.330 --> 00:56:56.913
This is going to
become a lot clearer,

00:56:56.913 --> 00:56:58.810
as I talk to you about
the physics that's

00:56:58.810 --> 00:57:04.790
missing in pair potentials
and how you correct to that.

00:57:04.790 --> 00:57:05.290
OK.

00:57:08.170 --> 00:57:12.190
So I tried to find
what I thought

00:57:12.190 --> 00:57:16.150
is maybe the first example
of computational modeling

00:57:16.150 --> 00:57:18.490
with potentials.

00:57:18.490 --> 00:57:21.580
It's probably not the first, but
I think maybe one of the first

00:57:21.580 --> 00:57:24.430
that was done on computer.

00:57:24.430 --> 00:57:27.700
This was done by
Vineyard's group,

00:57:27.700 --> 00:57:31.870
and it's essentially studying
radiation damage in copper.

00:57:31.870 --> 00:57:35.350
This is from 1960.

00:57:35.350 --> 00:57:37.930
I don't know if you remember
punch cards for computers.

00:57:37.930 --> 00:57:39.910
I think this is from
before punch cards.

00:57:42.820 --> 00:57:46.960
But they managed to program
a small molecular dynamics,

00:57:46.960 --> 00:57:48.400
and essentially
what they're doing

00:57:48.400 --> 00:57:51.670
is they have a crystal of
copper, and they're shooting--

00:57:51.670 --> 00:57:56.460
I think they're
shooting some ions in it

00:57:56.460 --> 00:58:00.360
to actually see the orbit that
the radiation damage falls.

00:58:00.360 --> 00:58:02.610
So you knock out atoms, and
you show the displacement.

00:58:02.610 --> 00:58:06.180
Ironically, this is a simulation
people still do these days.

00:58:06.180 --> 00:58:13.500
Molecular dynamics on
radiation damage, so 1960.

00:58:13.500 --> 00:58:14.520
OK.

00:58:14.520 --> 00:58:19.890
So let me talk a little
about the obvious problems

00:58:19.890 --> 00:58:22.650
with pair potentials, and
this is one of the things

00:58:22.650 --> 00:58:26.055
that we're going to then
show you in the lab.

00:58:26.055 --> 00:58:27.930
We are actually going
to make you demonstrate

00:58:27.930 --> 00:58:31.320
this in the lab, and
once you understand

00:58:31.320 --> 00:58:33.780
the physical limitations
of pair potential,

00:58:33.780 --> 00:58:37.410
you'll see that the solutions
which is pair functional

00:58:37.410 --> 00:58:39.630
methods or cluster
potential are actually quite

00:58:39.630 --> 00:58:42.370
obvious why they came about.

00:58:42.370 --> 00:58:44.670
And when I talk about
failures of pair potentials,

00:58:44.670 --> 00:58:47.220
I don't talk about
failures of the parameters.

00:58:47.220 --> 00:58:49.480
I talk about
failures of the form,

00:58:49.480 --> 00:58:51.930
and there's a lot of
people who say, well,

00:58:51.930 --> 00:58:54.750
if this doesn't work, I just
need to change my parameters

00:58:54.750 --> 00:58:55.710
in my potential.

00:58:55.710 --> 00:58:57.690
There are certain things
that you can never

00:58:57.690 --> 00:59:00.570
get right with pair
potentials, because they

00:59:00.570 --> 00:59:05.340
are in violation of the
particular form which

00:59:05.340 --> 00:59:08.820
is a pairwise interaction.

00:59:08.820 --> 00:59:13.530
So one is, obviously, that
pair potentials count bonds.

00:59:13.530 --> 00:59:16.320
That's what you
should keep in mind.

00:59:16.320 --> 00:59:18.150
They really essentially sum--

00:59:18.150 --> 00:59:19.980
the cohesive energy
on an atom is largely

00:59:19.980 --> 00:59:22.650
determined by how many things
are around it, because it

00:59:22.650 --> 00:59:24.490
literally sums bonds around it.

00:59:24.490 --> 00:59:27.940
It doesn't care much about
the organization of atoms.

00:59:27.940 --> 00:59:33.910
So if you take this
triangle, let's say

00:59:33.910 --> 00:59:37.510
these bonds are
one Angstrom, or I

00:59:37.510 --> 00:59:42.430
take this chain, where the
bonds are one Angstrom.

00:59:42.430 --> 00:59:42.930
OK?

00:59:42.930 --> 00:59:45.000
Here, I have four atoms,
here I have three,

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:47.470
but there are three
bonds in each case.

00:59:47.470 --> 00:59:49.590
These have essentially
the same energy

00:59:49.590 --> 00:59:51.660
in a pair potential model.

00:59:51.660 --> 00:59:53.220
OK?

00:59:53.220 --> 00:59:55.770
The only thing that
would distinguish them

00:59:55.770 --> 01:00:02.700
is longer range
interactions, but that's not

01:00:02.700 --> 01:00:06.220
the physics that in many
cases makes this different.

01:00:06.220 --> 01:00:06.993
OK?

01:00:06.993 --> 01:00:09.160
The physics that in many
cases makes this different,

01:00:09.160 --> 01:00:11.710
for example, could
be angular or bonding

01:00:11.710 --> 01:00:14.170
or could be that
the presence of this

01:00:14.170 --> 01:00:17.950
truly influences the
bond between these two.

01:00:17.950 --> 01:00:22.120
And we'll actually show you
how to solve both problems.

01:00:22.120 --> 01:00:23.890
They're actually
different problems that

01:00:23.890 --> 01:00:25.300
lead to different solutions.

01:00:27.860 --> 01:00:33.480
Another nice example, if you
take a ethylene molecule,

01:00:33.480 --> 01:00:35.880
let's say you were
trying to model

01:00:35.880 --> 01:00:39.300
that with pair potentials.

01:00:39.300 --> 01:00:45.370
If I flap these bonds here,
so I bend open the hydrogens,

01:00:45.370 --> 01:00:47.880
that really doesn't
cost me any energy,

01:00:47.880 --> 01:00:49.420
if I have a pair potential.

01:00:49.420 --> 01:00:49.920
OK?

01:00:49.920 --> 01:00:52.650
Because the pair potential
just measures this distance

01:00:52.650 --> 01:00:54.160
and this distance.

01:00:54.160 --> 01:00:57.510
So if I just flap this open,
that distance stays the same.

01:00:57.510 --> 01:01:00.120
OK?

01:01:00.120 --> 01:01:02.220
Only if you had some
indirect interaction

01:01:02.220 --> 01:01:05.250
between these
hydrogens would you

01:01:05.250 --> 01:01:08.820
pick up that energy difference.

01:01:08.820 --> 01:01:11.340
But you see, if you
made a potential

01:01:11.340 --> 01:01:14.880
between the hydrogens, you'd be
putting the wrong physics in.

01:01:14.880 --> 01:01:17.707
Because the reason that energy
changes, as I change that band,

01:01:17.707 --> 01:01:19.290
has nothing to do
with the interaction

01:01:19.290 --> 01:01:20.940
between the hydrogens.

01:01:20.940 --> 01:01:24.720
But it has all to do with the
hybridization of the carbon,

01:01:24.720 --> 01:01:28.400
that the carbon is sp2
hybridized and one certain bond

01:01:28.400 --> 01:01:29.510
angles.

01:01:29.510 --> 01:01:30.210
OK?

01:01:30.210 --> 01:01:34.800
So it's not because you can
fix it with pair potentials

01:01:34.800 --> 01:01:35.850
that you fix it right.

01:01:40.550 --> 01:01:42.230
OK.

01:01:42.230 --> 01:01:45.470
The other thing you will see
is, if you use pair potentials,

01:01:45.470 --> 01:01:48.650
and you look say for low
energy crystal structures,

01:01:48.650 --> 01:01:52.710
you will almost always end
up in close-packed systems.

01:01:52.710 --> 01:01:55.310
And the reason is that
in pair potential models,

01:01:55.310 --> 01:01:59.240
atoms try to maximize their
coordination, because really

01:01:59.240 --> 01:02:04.320
you sum the energy pairwise
coming from atoms around you.

01:02:04.320 --> 01:02:08.090
So if you have a
negative bonding energy

01:02:08.090 --> 01:02:10.010
with atoms around
you, you try to get

01:02:10.010 --> 01:02:13.430
as many as you can
around you, so you

01:02:13.430 --> 01:02:16.040
will maximize coordination.

01:02:16.040 --> 01:02:19.610
The ground states of most
potential models for elements

01:02:19.610 --> 01:02:24.520
are HCP Hexagonal Close-Packed
and FCC Face-Centered

01:02:24.520 --> 01:02:25.610
Close-Packed.

01:02:25.610 --> 01:02:26.360
OK?

01:02:26.360 --> 01:02:28.640
So it's extremely hard
to stabilize things

01:02:28.640 --> 01:02:31.240
like a diamond cubic structure
which is an open structure.

01:02:31.240 --> 01:02:32.990
I don't know if you
have a picture for it.

01:02:37.050 --> 01:02:42.290
The other thing which
is maybe more obvious,

01:02:42.290 --> 01:02:46.445
but pair potentials are
not stable against shear,

01:02:46.445 --> 01:02:48.320
and now you could argue
most materials aren't

01:02:48.320 --> 01:02:49.400
stable against shear.

01:02:49.400 --> 01:02:53.960
But if I take the
square of atoms--

01:02:53.960 --> 01:02:56.480
let's say this is just
a piece of a lattice.

01:02:56.480 --> 01:03:07.280
OK-- if I shear this, I
can shear this and keep

01:03:07.280 --> 01:03:09.140
all these distances the same.

01:03:15.270 --> 01:03:17.480
So in a nearest
neighbor pair potential,

01:03:17.480 --> 01:03:20.215
all the energy has not changed.

01:03:20.215 --> 01:03:21.590
So if the energy
has not changed,

01:03:21.590 --> 01:03:25.340
that means that my elastic
constant in shear is 0.

01:03:25.340 --> 01:03:26.150
OK?

01:03:26.150 --> 01:03:29.990
Now, you could say, this is why
real materials on form square

01:03:29.990 --> 01:03:32.330
lattices and simple
cubic lattice, and that's

01:03:32.330 --> 01:03:33.560
actually true.

01:03:33.560 --> 01:03:36.290
But a real material has
some amount of resistance

01:03:36.290 --> 01:03:40.050
against shear, even in
a square configuration.

01:03:40.050 --> 01:03:41.780
And here you see
by construction,

01:03:41.780 --> 01:03:47.000
it doesn't have any resistance.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:47.500
OK.

01:04:02.540 --> 01:04:07.490
What I'm going to do is
try to break down what

01:04:07.490 --> 01:04:12.440
in different materials classes,
like metals or organic solids,

01:04:12.440 --> 01:04:15.560
what the failures
of pair potentials,

01:04:15.560 --> 01:04:20.190
and then we'll go into what
the remedies are for that.

01:04:20.190 --> 01:04:25.040
So in metals, the main
thing is this problem.

01:04:25.040 --> 01:04:27.230
That if you do a
pair potential model,

01:04:27.230 --> 01:04:29.990
and you look at the bonding
energy of this red atom,

01:04:29.990 --> 01:04:31.940
it's really
essentially six times

01:04:31.940 --> 01:04:35.840
the single bond energy of
the red with the white one.

01:04:35.840 --> 01:04:39.080
And so that's why
for pair potentials,

01:04:39.080 --> 01:04:43.070
people say that cohesive
energy scales with Z which

01:04:43.070 --> 01:04:44.240
is the coordination number.

01:04:52.170 --> 01:04:56.580
And if you do quantum mechanics
or even more approximate theory

01:04:56.580 --> 01:04:59.710
but that have the essentials
of hybridization in them,

01:04:59.710 --> 01:05:03.120
you find that actually for
metals-- and with metals,

01:05:03.120 --> 01:05:06.570
I mean things that have
covalent delocalized bonding,

01:05:06.570 --> 01:05:09.690
which you call
metallic bonding--

01:05:09.690 --> 01:05:13.330
the cohesive energy of an atom
goes like the square root of Z.

01:05:13.330 --> 01:05:13.830
OK?

01:05:13.830 --> 01:05:16.060
So it's not linear in Z at all.

01:05:16.060 --> 01:05:18.780
So if you have more
bonds, you start

01:05:18.780 --> 01:05:21.240
gaining less and
less incrementally,

01:05:21.240 --> 01:05:22.230
and you can see that.

01:05:22.230 --> 01:05:23.500
I made a picture here.

01:05:23.500 --> 01:05:26.130
This is out of a, I think,
what's really a great article,

01:05:26.130 --> 01:05:27.750
if you want to read
more about this.

01:05:27.750 --> 01:05:30.810
It's a review article on
the embedded atom method.

01:05:30.810 --> 01:05:35.280
We'll put this on the restricted
side of the course website.

01:05:35.280 --> 01:05:38.520
This is actually for
nickel, the cohesive energy

01:05:38.520 --> 01:05:43.050
per atom as a function of
the coordination it's in.

01:05:43.050 --> 01:05:47.740
So of course, 12 here,
this is the FCC solid.

01:05:47.740 --> 01:05:51.000
2 is the dimer.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:53.823
So this is just two
atoms in the gas phase,

01:05:53.823 --> 01:05:54.990
and what do you think is 11?

01:05:59.590 --> 01:06:00.460
How do you get 11?

01:06:06.650 --> 01:06:08.750
This is actually
experimental data.

01:06:11.700 --> 01:06:15.000
11 is from the vacancy
formation energy.

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:18.240
If you make a vacancy in a
crystal, the atoms around it

01:06:18.240 --> 01:06:21.060
are 11-fold coordinated
instead of 12.

01:06:21.060 --> 01:06:24.270
In FCC, you have
12-fold coordination,

01:06:24.270 --> 01:06:27.240
but if you take an atom away,
those atoms around there

01:06:27.240 --> 01:06:28.710
have 11-fold coordination.

01:06:28.710 --> 01:06:30.750
So this comes from the
vacancy coordination.

01:06:30.750 --> 01:06:33.750
Now, there's three points here.

01:06:33.750 --> 01:06:36.378
They drew a square
root through them.

01:06:36.378 --> 01:06:37.920
You probably could
draw other things,

01:06:37.920 --> 01:06:39.670
but what we do know
from quantum mechanics

01:06:39.670 --> 01:06:42.720
is that essentially the first
order is square root of Z

01:06:42.720 --> 01:06:45.540
behavior and now Z behavior.

01:06:45.540 --> 01:06:48.930
You can also see
that in silicon.

01:06:48.930 --> 01:06:50.610
This is a slightly
confusing graph,

01:06:50.610 --> 01:06:56.190
but this is the energy per
bond in red for silicon

01:06:56.190 --> 01:06:58.460
in different coordinations.

01:06:58.460 --> 01:06:59.270
OK?

01:06:59.270 --> 01:07:04.820
So what you see is that
the energy per bond

01:07:04.820 --> 01:07:08.540
actually goes down as
you make more bonds.

01:07:08.540 --> 01:07:11.240
So even though as you
coordinate an atom

01:07:11.240 --> 01:07:13.730
with more atoms around it,
the total cohesive energy

01:07:13.730 --> 01:07:15.200
may go down.

01:07:15.200 --> 01:07:17.570
If you divide that energy
by the number of bonds,

01:07:17.570 --> 01:07:20.190
that number becomes
smaller and smaller.

01:07:20.190 --> 01:07:20.690
OK?

01:07:20.690 --> 01:07:23.690
It's almost like an atom
in a covalent bonding

01:07:23.690 --> 01:07:27.440
has only so much
bonding power to give,

01:07:27.440 --> 01:07:29.540
and if it only
bonds to one atom,

01:07:29.540 --> 01:07:32.030
it gives all its bonding
power to that one atom.

01:07:32.030 --> 01:07:33.620
If it has to bond
to a lot, it has

01:07:33.620 --> 01:07:36.770
to divide that
between all those.

01:07:36.770 --> 01:07:39.200
So this is an important
concept to remember,

01:07:39.200 --> 01:07:43.640
that in covalent
materials, cohesive energy

01:07:43.640 --> 01:07:46.070
is not linear in coordination.

01:07:46.070 --> 01:07:51.250
Bonding strength gets weaker,
as you add more bonds,

01:07:51.250 --> 01:07:53.240
and we'll come back to that.

01:07:53.240 --> 01:07:56.020
This is important
when you go between--

01:07:56.020 --> 01:07:58.690
when you make potentials in
one coordination environment

01:07:58.690 --> 01:08:00.220
and start using
them in another one.

01:08:07.950 --> 01:08:10.550
Here's a quantum mechanical
result for aluminum.

01:08:13.440 --> 01:08:16.880
So this is the
cohesive energy, again,

01:08:16.880 --> 01:08:18.960
as a function of the
coordination number.

01:08:18.960 --> 01:08:20.870
So this is actually
a calculation,

01:08:20.870 --> 01:08:25.160
and again what you see is that,
even though as you coordinate

01:08:25.160 --> 01:08:27.529
more the cohesive
energy goes down,

01:08:27.529 --> 01:08:29.182
but it doesn't go down linear.

01:08:29.182 --> 01:08:30.890
If you want to think
of it, the increment

01:08:30.890 --> 01:08:33.859
you're getting
from adding a bond

01:08:33.859 --> 01:08:35.930
starts getting
smaller and smaller.

01:08:35.930 --> 01:08:42.310
If you go from one
to two, you could say

01:08:42.310 --> 01:08:44.140
this is your bonding energy.

01:08:44.140 --> 01:08:45.700
This is the extra
energy you get.

01:08:45.700 --> 01:08:50.870
If you go from 11 to 12,
all you gain is this.

01:08:50.870 --> 01:08:53.380
So the bond energy, when
you go from the 11 to 12

01:08:53.380 --> 01:08:57.399
is much smaller than the bonding
energy when you go from 1 to 2.

01:08:57.399 --> 01:08:58.930
OK?

01:08:58.930 --> 01:09:02.439
So the cohesive energy
with coordination

01:09:02.439 --> 01:09:04.689
is a convex function.

01:09:04.689 --> 01:09:07.300
That's important
to keep in mind.

01:09:07.300 --> 01:09:09.970
And of course, you cannot get
that with pair potentials.

01:09:09.970 --> 01:09:12.550
With pair potentials, this
will essentially look linear.

01:09:15.700 --> 01:09:17.840
Now, what's the slope of
it in pair potentials?

01:09:23.390 --> 01:09:25.100
It's a trick question.

01:09:25.100 --> 01:09:26.470
What's the slope of that line?

01:09:36.920 --> 01:09:41.293
Well, Z's the coordinate, so
