01:10:44.430 --> 01:10:46.790
This is the pair
potential for copper

01:10:46.790 --> 01:10:50.430
fitted to different properties.

01:10:50.430 --> 01:10:54.720
The lowest one is the one fitted
to the dimer, to the molecule.

01:10:58.400 --> 01:11:03.310
So this is just a
copper-copper dimer.

01:11:03.310 --> 01:11:05.877
You see, it's the
strongest of them all.

01:11:05.877 --> 01:11:07.960
It's the strongest of all
the potentials, and why,

01:11:07.960 --> 01:11:10.160
because there's only one bond.

01:11:10.160 --> 01:11:10.970
OK?

01:11:10.970 --> 01:11:15.100
You remember, all the bonding
energy goes in that one bond.

01:11:15.100 --> 01:11:18.250
The equation of state,
that's essentially

01:11:18.250 --> 01:11:22.420
looking at the cohesive energy
of the solid as a function

01:11:22.420 --> 01:11:24.130
of lattice parameter.

01:11:24.130 --> 01:11:33.477
So this one, that's
almost the smallest one.

01:11:33.477 --> 01:11:34.185
That's the solid.

01:11:38.780 --> 01:11:41.960
See, a lot smaller,
because you're counting now

01:11:41.960 --> 01:11:46.380
bond strength in coordination
12, where every bond is weaker.

01:11:46.380 --> 01:11:48.860
So you try to map that
onto a pair potential,

01:11:48.860 --> 01:11:51.665
and you get, in some sense,
a much weaker interaction

01:11:51.665 --> 01:11:54.500
per pair.

01:11:54.500 --> 01:11:57.885
And what Anders Karlsson did, he
also extracted it from phonons.

01:11:57.885 --> 01:11:58.760
This is actually one.

01:11:58.760 --> 01:12:01.610
It's really small
and from defects,

01:12:01.610 --> 01:12:03.677
and the defect one even
