01:12:09.110 --> 01:12:13.310
So what this is telling you,
what I'm trying to demonstrate,

01:12:13.310 --> 01:12:17.690
is that for metals and for
anything that's actually

01:12:17.690 --> 01:12:22.520
covalent, but this is worse
for covalent delocalized,

01:12:22.520 --> 01:12:25.220
your potential is extremely
environment-dependent.

01:12:25.220 --> 01:12:27.950
It's essentially
coordination-dependent.

01:12:27.950 --> 01:12:28.610
OK?

01:12:28.610 --> 01:12:32.990
And we show you in
the next lecture

01:12:32.990 --> 01:12:37.850
how that shows up in
certain physical properties

01:12:37.850 --> 01:12:39.350
and then how you solve that.

01:12:39.350 --> 01:12:42.110
Because turns out, there's
a very elegant solution

01:12:42.110 --> 01:12:44.840
to the problem, and I
think you can already see

01:12:44.840 --> 01:12:46.550
where we're going to take this.

01:12:46.550 --> 01:12:48.890
The problem is that
our bonding energy

01:12:48.890 --> 01:12:52.530
is linear in coordination
with a pair potential.

01:12:52.530 --> 01:12:55.190
So all we need to do
to fix this problem is

01:12:55.190 --> 01:12:58.760
to make it nonlinear,
and that leads you

01:12:58.760 --> 01:13:01.760
into what are called pair
functionals, rather than pair

01:13:01.760 --> 01:13:03.020
potentials.

01:13:03.020 --> 01:13:05.960
And things like there's a
whole class of methods, things

01:13:05.960 --> 01:13:09.140
like the embedded atom
method, glue models,

01:13:09.140 --> 01:13:11.480
effective medium theory, they
all go be different names,

01:13:11.480 --> 01:13:14.630
are essentially pair
functional models.

01:13:14.630 --> 01:13:16.340
There are still
things that count

01:13:16.340 --> 01:13:20.090
the coordination around you
in some form or another.

01:13:20.090 --> 01:13:23.450
It's just that they make
the energy evolve nonlinear

01:13:23.450 --> 01:13:26.692
with that coordination, and
they're very elegant methods.

01:13:26.692 --> 01:13:28.400
They're still empirical
methods, but very

01:13:28.400 --> 01:13:31.610
elegant methods that solve
the essential problem of pair

01:13:31.610 --> 01:13:34.410
potentials without
a lot of extra work,

01:13:34.410 --> 01:13:37.862
and so we'll talk
about that on Thursday.

